  "text": "Soil management can manipulate the balance of carbon sink and source processes. When OM is broken down, some of the SOC can be quickly mineralized and converted to CO 2 . Carbon thus disappears from the soil. The high amount of soil organic matter tends to be limited to the soil surface, probably at a depth of 5 to 10 cm [CITATION_1] . Organic matter often binds to fine particles, particularly clay, and the binding processes further prevent soil carbon loss [CITATION_2] . The study of SOC and its relationship to OM is important; yet there are research gaps to be filled regarding mangrove soils in Thailand. It is still questionable how much SOC is stored in the wetland soils and to what extent SOC is related to OM. The aim of this study is to spatially investigate the SOC content in mangrove areas at surface and subsurface layers, as well as the association of SOC-to-OM conversion. The result of the conversion factor from this study is useful for estimating either SOC or OM in similar environments. The specific objectives of this study are threefold:",
